out three weeks with a foot injury. It might have been the Tritons' best season 
since 1978, now there's too many questions and too few answers. What's left is 
Castaneda, who is a returning starter, but averaged 3.3 points. He'll need to 
improve his scoring output. Johnson is being asked to take on an awful lot for 
a freshman. Perry saw limited playing time a year ago, but is an excellent 
shooter. Gardner is big, but thin, and did not play last year. Under normal 
circumstances, he would be a project, but he'll probably be the Tritons' center 
