<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANGELS MAKE THEIR PITCH TO BRING BACK WILD THING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Angels, who tried to coax closer Mitch Williams out of retirement last 
summer, are at it again. According to sources, they have offered Williams a 
non-guaranteed contract for the 1995 season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels hope to acquire Williams as their left-handed setup man, club 
officials said, and get free agent Lee Smith as their closer. 
</P>
<P>
 Williams, 30, retired from baseball last June after he was released by the 
Astros. The Angels telephoned at least 10 times to persuade him to be their 
closer, Williams said, but he had no interest in returning. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, after spending the last five months on his Texas ranch, Williams says 
he's ready to pitch. He says he refuses to be haunted by two blown saves in the 
1993 World Series. "I know I can still pitch," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 In other news, the Angels have decided not to offer Bo Jackson and Rex Hudler 
arbitration by the Dec. 7 deadline, leaving them only eight days to reach an 
agreement with their free agents or lose the rights to negotiate with them 
until May 1, 1995. "We still have some interest in each of them," General 
Manager Bill Bavasi said, "but we're not going to offer arbitration. We'll see 
what happens in the next week." 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, the Angels remain interested in free agent Mickey Tettleton. 
Tettleton, who is seeking a four-year, $12 million contract, has had 
preliminary talks with the Angels about a two-year contract with at least one 
option year. 
</P>
<P>
 Tettleton, 34, hit at least 31 homers in each of the last three seasons until 
the strike interrupted the 1994 season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels also released the official schedule for their 35th anniversary 
season. They'll open the 1995 season against the Brewers April 4 at Anaheim 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 The spring training schedule (all games noon PST unless indicated): 
</P>
