<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; RAMS; RUBLEY RELEASED AFTER PASSING ON DEAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 T.J. Rubley, who finished last season as the Rams' starting quarterback, was 
released Tuesday because he recently rejected a contract offer for next season. 
</P>
<P>
 "They offered a deal three weeks ago and we elected not to take it," Rubley 
said. "They were disappointed, and I anticipated this might happen. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just want the chance to see the field, and I don't believe I fit in their 
plans. I could have signed the contract, but a contract doesn't mean anything 
until the first week of the regular season, and I'd rather start fresh now than 
be released the last week of training camp." 
</P>
<P>
 Rubley started seven games a year ago, including a 20-6 victory in the season 
finale over the Bears. But when the Rams signed him to a one-year deal this 
past summer, they made it clear they were more interested in Chris Miller and 
Chris Chandler. 
</P>
<P>
 "The only disappointment in this whole thing is trying to be someone's 
quarterback and living up to what they expect and then turning around and 
seeing them pay someone else three and four times as much to play the 
position," Rubley said. "That devastated me. I didn't understand what they were 
doing." 
</P>
<P>
 An elbow injury, which he kept secret several months, further handicapped 
Rubley's standing with the team. Coaches were troubled by his poor performance 
in off-season workouts not knowing he was throwing in pain. The elbow 
irritation finally forced the team to place him on injured reserve for the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 Rubley completed 108 of 189 passes (57.1%) for 1,338 yards with eight 
touchdowns and six interceptions last season; in comparison, Miller has 
completed 51.9% of his passes, including 12 touchdowns and 13 interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just love the game in its purist form," he said. "Take away the business 
side and it would be that much more fun. But that's all right. I'll just start 
at ground zero again and find somewhere where I can compete as a backup and 
then see what happens. If nothing materializes, I'll be at peace and just be a 
weekend warrior." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Rams also released guard Brad Fichtel to make room for the expected 
addition of wide receiver Jermaine Ross later this week. If Fichtel clears 
waivers, the Rams intend to add him to their practice squad. T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</TEXT>
