<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY GRANT WILL BUY COMPUTERS FOR SENIOR CITIZENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BILLITER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 County Supervisor Harriett M. Wieder this week presented Cypress with a $5,000 
county grant to be used for computers for senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
 The money will also buy computer programs and other software to be used with 
the new equipment, said Marvin DeCarlo, the city's director of recreation and 
parks. 
</P>
<P>
 "The new computers will be placed in the senior citizen center, and the 
seniors will be able to use the computers to network with other seniors on 
computers," DeCarlo said. "This money from the county is a much-appreciated 
gift and will be put to immediate use." 
</P>
<P>
 Wieder, whose supervisorial district includes Cypress, came in person to 
present the money as part of her farewell to elective office. She declined to 
seek reelection Nov. 8 and will retire after this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's my swan song," Wieder told the council and council audience. "We've come 
a long, long way in the 16 years that I've served the 2nd (Supervisorial) 
District and the city of Cypress." 
</P>
<P>
 Council members, in thanking Wieder for the funds, also praised her years on 
the County Board of Supervisors. They said that Wieder, a former Huntington 
Beach mayor, had been diligent in caring for the needs of cities in her 
district. 
</P>
