<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY BRIEFLY: FLUOR SUBSIDIARY TO WORK ON FUEL CELL POWER PLANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fluor Corp.'s Fluor Daniel Inc. subsidiary and a unit of Energy Research Corp. 
in Danbury, Conn., said Monday they have signed an agreement to cooperate on 
commercial development of fuel cell power plants. 
</P>
<P>
 Financial terms were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
 The companies have agreed to cooperate on sales, installation and support 
services, development of international markets and securing financing for 
demonstration projects. 
</P>
<P>
 Direct fuel cell power plants produce electricity by combining hydrogen in the 
fuel with oxygen in the air to produce electricity and water. There are 
virtually no toxic emissions because the fuel isn't burned. Current models use 
natural gas as fuel, although alternative fuels, such as ethanol and 
coal-derived gas, are being studied. 
</P>
<P>
 The two companies are working on a demonstration project in Santa Clara that 
would be capable of supplying electricity to 1,500 homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
